<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Sip (Character Type) - CURSED Programming Language</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="../styles/docs.css">
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Outfit:wght@400;500;600;700;800&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;700&display=swap" rel="stylesheet">
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <div class="container">
            <h1><span class="gradient-text">💧 The Sip Type 💧</span></h1>
            <p class="subtitle">One character, infinite possibilities!</p>
        </div>
    </header>

    <main class="container">
        <div class="doc-grid">
            <aside class="sidebar">
                <nav>
                    <ul>
                        <li><a href="basic-types.html">Basic Types</a></li>
                        <li><a href="string-literal.html">String Literals</a></li>
                        <li><a href="#" class="active">Sip (Character)</a></li>
                        <li><a href="stringz.html">Stringz</a></li>
                        <li><a href="arrays-slices.html">Arrays & Slices</a></li>
                    </ul>
                </nav>
            </aside>

            <article class="content">
                <section class="intro">
                    <div class="tag-container">
                        <span class="tag">Basic Type</span>
                        <span class="tag">Unicode</span>
                        <span class="tag">Character</span>
                    </div>
                    <p class="lead">The <code>sip</code> type represents a single Unicode character (or rune). Think of it as taking just a sip of a string - a single character at a time!</p>
                </section>

                <section>
                    <h2>✨ What's a Sip? ✨</h2>
                    <p>In CURSED, a <code>sip</code> is a 32-bit integer (equivalent to <code>rune</code>) that represents a single Unicode code point. This means it can represent any character in the Unicode standard, including emoji and characters from pretty much any language!</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">sip_basics.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>// Declaring sip variables
sus a sip = 'a';            // Latin letter
sus emoji sip = '🔥';       // Fire emoji
sus kanji sip = '語';       // Japanese character

// The zero value is the null character
sus zero_sip sip;           // Value is '\0'</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section>
                    <h2>🧙‍♂️ Sip Operations 🧙‍♂️</h2>
                    <p>The <code>sip</code> type comes with built-in methods that let you vibe with your characters:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">sip_operations.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>sus c sip = 'A';

// Character classification
sus is_upper lit = c.is_uppercase();   // true for 'A'
sus is_lower lit = c.is_lowercase();   // false for 'A'
sus is_digit lit = c.is_digit();       // false for 'A'
sus is_alpha lit = c.is_alpha();       // true for 'A'
sus is_alnum lit = c.is_alnum();       // true for 'A'

// Character transformation
sus as_lower sip = c.to_lowercase();   // 'a'
sus as_upper sip = 'b'.to_uppercase(); // 'B'</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="conversion-section">
                    <h2>🔄 Type Conversion 🔄</h2>
                    <p>You can convert between <code>sip</code> and numeric types, which is super useful for character manipulation:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">sip_conversion.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>// Character to number
sus c sip = 'A';
sus code normie = normie(c);         // 65 (ASCII value of 'A')

// Number to character
sus n normie = 66;
sus letter sip = sip(n);             // 'B'

// Unicode code point to character
sus fire sip = sip(0x1F525);        // '🔥' (Unicode U+1F525)</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="example-section">
                    <h2>🌈 Sipping in Action 🌈</h2>
                    <p>Here's a practical example showing how to use the <code>sip</code> type for iterating through a string:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">character_counter.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>yeet "stringz";

slay countUppercase(text tea) normie {
    sus count normie = 0;
    
    // Iterate through characters in the string
    for (sus i = 0; i < text.length(); i++) {
        sus char sip = text.charAt(i);  // Get character at position
        
        if (char.is_uppercase()) {
            count++;
        }
    }
    
    yolo count;
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="tips">
                    <h2>Bestie Advice 💅</h2>
                    <div class="tips-grid">
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">👑</div>
                            <h3>Unicode Aware</h3>
                            <p>Remember that <code>sip</code> stores Unicode code points, which might be different from what you visually see as a single character!</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">📏</div>
                            <h3>Size Matters</h3>
                            <p>A <code>sip</code> is 32 bits (4 bytes), which is larger than what you might expect from a "character" if you're coming from other languages.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">🔤</div>
                            <h3>String Connection</h3>
                            <p>Strings (<code>tea</code>) in CURSED are sequences of <code>sip</code> characters, not just bytes!</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">💯</div>
                            <h3>Literal Syntax</h3>
                            <p>Always use single quotes for <code>sip</code> literals: <code>'a'</code>, not <code>"a"</code> which would be a <code>tea</code> (string).</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="example-section">
                    <h2>🎨 Advanced Sipping 🎨</h2>
                    <p>Here's a more complex example showing how to create a simple character utility:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">case_flipper.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>slay flipCase(input tea) tea {
    sus result tea = "";
    
    for (sus i = 0; i < input.length(); i++) {
        sus c sip = input.charAt(i);
        
        if (c.is_uppercase()) {
            result = result + tea(c.to_lowercase());
        } else if (c.is_lowercase()) {
            result = result + tea(c.to_uppercase());
        } else {
            // Not a letter, just keep it as is
            result = result + tea(c);
        }
    }
    
    yolo result;
}

// Usage:
// flipCase("Hello World!") returns "hELLO wORLD!"</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="faq">
                    <h2>Quick FAQs ❓</h2>
                    <div class="accordion">
                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <div class="accordion-header">What's the difference between <code>sip</code> and <code>byte</code>?</div>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>A <code>sip</code> is a 32-bit Unicode code point that can represent any character. A <code>byte</code> is just 8 bits and can only represent ASCII characters and raw binary data.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <div class="accordion-header">Can <code>sip</code> handle emoji?</div>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>Yes! <code>sip</code> can represent any single Unicode code point, including emoji. However, some complex emoji are composed of multiple code points and might require special handling.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="accordion-item">
                            <div class="accordion-header">Why is it called <code>sip</code>?</div>
                            <div class="accordion-content">
                                <p>Just like taking a sip of a drink is getting just a small amount, a <code>sip</code> in CURSED is just a small piece (one character) of a whole string (<code>tea</code>). It's giving wordplay vibes!</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="next-steps">
                    <h2>Keep The Vibe Going</h2>
                    <div class="next-links">
                        <a href="stringz.html" class="next-link">
                            <span class="next-link-text">Explore Stringz</span>
                            <span class="next-link-arrow">→</span>
                        </a>
                        <a href="string-literal.html" class="next-link">
